Helper for the tests below that test the extents of various axes elements
7153def color_boxes(fig, ax):
7154 """
7155 Helper for the tests below that test the extents of various axes elements
7156 """
7157 fig.canvas.draw()
7158
7159 renderer = fig.canvas.get_renderer()
7160 bbaxis = []
7161 for nn, axx in enumerate([ax.xaxis, ax.yaxis]):
7162 bb = axx.get_tightbbox(renderer)
7163 if bb:
7164 axisr = mpatches.Rectangle(
7165 (bb.x0, bb.y0), width=bb.width, height=bb.height,
7166 linewidth=0.7, edgecolor='y', facecolor="none", transform=None,
7167 zorder=3)
7168 fig.add_artist(axisr)
7169 bbaxis += [bb]
7170

6107def generate_errorbar_inputs():

6109 err_cycler = cycler('err', [1,
6110 [1, 1, 1, 1, 1],
6111 [[1, 1, 1, 1, 1],
6112 [1, 1, 1, 1, 1]],
6113 np.ones(5),
6114 np.ones((2, 5)),
6115 None
6116 ])

6118 yerr_cy = cycler('yerr', err_cycler)
6119
6120 empty = ((cycler('x', [[]]) + cycler('y', [[]])) *
6121 cycler('xerr', [[], None]) * cycler('yerr', [[], None]))
6122 xerr_only = base_xy * xerr_cy
6123 yerr_only = base_xy * yerr_cy
6124 both_err = base_xy * yerr_cy * xerr_cy
6125
6126 return [*xerr_only, *yerr_only, *both_err, *empty]

6275def shared_axes_generator(request):
6276 # test all of the ways to get fig/ax sets
6277 if request.param == 'gca':
6278 fig = plt.figure()
6279 ax = fig.gca()
6280 elif request.param == 'subplots':
6281 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
6282 elif request.param == 'subplots_shared':
6283 fig, ax_lst = plt.subplots(2, 2, sharex='all', sharey='all')
6284 ax = ax_lst[0][0]
6285 elif request.param == 'add_axes':
6286 fig = plt.figure()
6287 ax = fig.add_axes([.1, .1, .8, .8])
6288 return fig, ax

155def test_acorr(fig_test, fig_ref):
156 np.random.seed(19680801)
157 Nx = 512
158 x = np.random.normal(0, 1, Nx).cumsum()
159 maxlags = Nx-1
160
161 ax_test = fig_test.subplots()
162 ax_test.acorr(x, maxlags=maxlags)
163
164 ax_ref = fig_ref.subplots()
165 # Normalized autocorrelation
166 norm_auto_corr = np.correlate(x, x, mode="full")/np.dot(x, x)
167 lags = np.arange(-maxlags, maxlags+1)
168 norm_auto_corr = norm_auto_corr[Nx-1-maxlags:Nx+maxlags]
169 ax_ref.vlines(lags, [0], norm_auto_corr)
170 ax_ref.axhline(y=0, xmin=0, xmax=1)
171

1454def test_arc_angles():

1456 w = 2

1459 scale = 2
1460

1463 theta2 = i * 360 / 9
1464 theta1 = theta2 - 45
1465
1466 ax.add_patch(mpatches.Ellipse(centre, w, h, alpha=0.3))
1467 ax.add_patch(mpatches.Arc(centre, w, h, theta1=theta1, theta2=theta2))

1469 ax.plot([scale * np.cos(np.deg2rad(theta1)) + centre[0],
1470 centre[0],
1471 scale * np.cos(np.deg2rad(theta2)) + centre[0]],
1472 [scale * np.sin(np.deg2rad(theta1)) + centre[1],
1473 centre[1],
1474 scale * np.sin(np.deg2rad(theta2)) + centre[1]])
1475
1476 ax.set_xlim(-scale, scale)
1477 ax.set_ylim(-scale, scale)
1478

1480 # gets large enough.
1481 w *= 10
1482 h *= 10
1483 centre = (centre[0] * 10, centre[1] * 10)
1484 scale *= 10

1488def test_arc_ellipse():
1489 xcenter, ycenter = 0.38, 0.52
1490 width, height = 1e-1, 3e-1
1491 angle = -30
1492
1493 theta = np.deg2rad(np.arange(360))

1495 y = height / 2. * np.sin(theta)
1496

1498 R = np.array([
1499 [np.cos(rtheta), -np.sin(rtheta)],
1500 [np.sin(rtheta), np.cos(rtheta)]])
1501

1503 x += xcenter
1504 y += ycenter
1505
1506 fig = plt.figure()

1509 linewidth=1, zorder=1)

1512 angle=angle, linewidth=2, fill=False, zorder=2)
1513
1514 ax.add_patch(e1)
1515
1516 ax = fig.add_subplot(212, aspect='equal')
1517 ax.fill(x, y, alpha=0.2, facecolor='green', edgecolor='green', zorder=1)
1518 e2 = mpatches.Arc((xcenter, ycenter), width, height,
1519 angle=angle, linewidth=2, fill=False, zorder=2)

661def test_arrow_simple():
662 # Simple image test for ax.arrow
663 # kwargs that take discrete values
664 length_includes_head = (True, False)
665 shape = ('full', 'left', 'right')
666 head_starts_at_zero = (True, False)
667 # Create outer product of values
668 kwargs = product(length_includes_head, shape, head_starts_at_zero)

673 ax.set_ylim(-2, 2)

676 theta = 2 * np.pi * i / 12
677 # Draw arrow

679 width=theta/100,
680 length_includes_head=length_includes_head,
681 shape=shape,
682 head_starts_at_zero=head_starts_at_zero,
683 head_width=theta / 10,
684 head_length=theta / 10)

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_artist_sublists ( )
7893def test_artist_sublists():
7894 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
7895 lines = [ax.plot(np.arange(i, i + 5))[0] for i in range(6)]
7896 col = ax.scatter(np.arange(5), np.arange(5))
7897 im = ax.imshow(np.zeros((5, 5)))
7898 patch = ax.add_patch(mpatches.Rectangle((0, 0), 5, 5))
7899 text = ax.text(0, 0, 'foo')
7900
7901 # Get items, which should not be mixed.
7902 assert list(ax.collections) == [col]
7903 assert list(ax.images) == [im]
7904 assert list(ax.lines) == lines
7905 assert list(ax.patches) == [patch]
7906 assert not ax.tables
7907 assert list(ax.texts) == [text]
7908
7909 # Get items should work like lists/tuple.
7910 assert ax.lines[0] is lines[0]
7911 assert ax.lines[-1] is lines[-1]
7912 with pytest.raises(IndexError, match='out of range'):
7913 ax.lines[len(lines) + 1]
7914
7915 # Deleting items (multiple or single) should warn.
7916 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7917 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7918 del ax.lines[-1]
7919 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7920 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7921 del ax.lines[-1:]
7922 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7923 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7924 del ax.lines[1:]
7925 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7926 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7927 del ax.lines[0]
7928
7929 # Lists should be empty after removing items.
7930 col.remove()
7931 assert not ax.collections
7932 im.remove()
7933 assert not ax.images
7934 patch.remove()
7935 assert not ax.patches
7936 text.remove()
7937 assert not ax.texts
7938
7939 # Everything else should remain empty.
7940 assert not ax.lines
7941 assert not ax.tables
7942
7943 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7944 match='modification of the Axes.texts property'):
7945 ax.texts.append(text)
7946 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7947 match='modification of the Axes.collections property'):
7948 ax.collections.append(col)
7949 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7950 match='modification of the Axes.images property'):
7951 ax.images.append(im)
7952 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7953 match='modification of the Axes.patches property'):
7954 ax.patches.append(patch)
7955 # verify things are back
7956 assert list(ax.collections) == [col]
7957 assert list(ax.images) == [im]
7958 assert list(ax.patches) == [patch]
7959 assert list(ax.texts) == [text]
7960
7961 # Adding items should warn.
7962 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7963 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7964 ax.lines.append(lines[-2])
7965 assert list(ax.lines) == [lines[-2]]
7966 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7967 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7968 ax.lines.append(lines[-1])
7969 assert list(ax.lines) == lines[-2:]
7970 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7971 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7972 ax.lines.insert(-2, lines[0])
7973 assert list(ax.lines) == [lines[0], lines[-2], lines[-1]]
7974
7975 # Modifying items should warn.
7976 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7977 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7978 ax.lines[0] = lines[0]
7979 assert list(ax.lines) == [lines[0], lines[-2], lines[-1]]
7980 with pytest.warns(MatplotlibDeprecationWarning,
7981 match='modification of the Axes.lines property'):
7982 ax.lines[1:1] = lines[1:-2]
7983 assert list(ax.lines) == lines
7984
7985 # Adding to other lists should produce a regular list.
7986 assert ax.lines + [1, 2, 3] == [*lines, 1, 2, 3]
7987 assert [1, 2, 3] + ax.lines == [1, 2, 3, *lines]
7988
7989 for ln in ax.lines:
7990 ln.remove()
7991 assert len(ax.lines) == 0
7992

2751def test_as_mpl_axes_api():
2752 # tests the _as_mpl_axes api
2753 class Polar:
2754 def __init__(self):
2755 self.theta_offset = 0
2756
2757 def _as_mpl_axes(self):
2758 # implement the matplotlib axes interface
2759 return PolarAxes, {'theta_offset': self.theta_offset}
2760
2761 prj = Polar()
2762 prj2 = Polar()
2763 prj2.theta_offset = np.pi
2764
2765 # testing axes creation with plt.axes
2766 ax = plt.axes([0, 0, 1, 1], projection=prj)
2767 assert type(ax) == PolarAxes
2768 plt.close()
2769

593def test_autoscale_log_shared():
594 # related to github #7587
595 # array starts at zero to trigger _minpos handling
596 x = np.arange(100, dtype=float)
597 fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1, sharex=True)

599 ax2.semilogx(x, x)
600 ax1.autoscale(tight=True)
601 ax2.autoscale(tight=True)
602 plt.draw()
603 lims = (x[1], x[-1])
604 assert_allclose(ax1.get_xlim(), lims)
605 assert_allclose(ax1.get_ylim(), lims)
606 assert_allclose(ax2.get_xlim(), lims)
607 assert_allclose(ax2.get_ylim(), (x[0], x[-1]))

6559def test_axisbelow():
6560 # Test 'line' setting added in 6287.
6561 # Show only grids, not frame or ticks, to make this test
6562 # independent of future change to drawing order of those elements.
6563 axs = plt.figure().subplots(ncols=3, sharex=True, sharey=True)
6564 settings = (False, 'line', True)
6565
6566 for ax, setting in zip(axs, settings):

6569 ax.add_patch(circ)
6570 ax.grid(color='c', linestyle='-', linewidth=3)
6571 ax.tick_params(top=False, bottom=False,
6572 left=False, right=False)
6573 ax.spines[:].set_visible(False)
6574 ax.set_axisbelow(setting)
6575 assert ax.get_axisbelow() == setting

7420def test_bar_errbar_zorder():

7422 # are plotted on

7428 for bar in barcont.patches:

◆ test_bar_leading_nan()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_bar_leading_nan ( )
8173def test_bar_leading_nan():
8174
8175 barx = np.arange(3, dtype=float)
8176 barheights = np.array([0.5, 1.5, 2.0])
8177 barstarts = np.array([0.77]*3)
8178
8179 barx[0] = np.NaN
8180
8181 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
8182
8183 bars = ax.bar(barx, barheights, bottom=barstarts)
8184
8185 hbars = ax.barh(barx, barheights, left=barstarts)
8186
8187 for bar_set in (bars, hbars):
8188 # the first bar should have a nan in the location
8189 nanful, *rest = bar_set
8190 assert (~np.isfinite(nanful.xy)).any()
8191 assert np.isfinite(nanful.get_width())
8192 for b in rest:
8193 assert np.isfinite(b.xy).all()
8194 assert np.isfinite(b.get_width())
8195

1904def test_bar_pandas(pd):
1905 # Smoke test for pandas
1906 df = pd.DataFrame(
1907 {'year': [2018, 2018, 2018],
1908 'month': [1, 1, 1],
1909 'day': [1, 2, 3],
1910 'value': [1, 2, 3]})
1911 df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df[['year', 'month', 'day']])
1912
1913 monthly = df[['date', 'value']].groupby(['date']).sum()
1914 dates = monthly.index
1915 forecast = monthly['value']
1916 baseline = monthly['value']
1917
1918 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1919 ax.bar(dates, forecast, width=10, align='center')
1920 ax.plot(dates, baseline, color='orange', lw=4)

8093 # Check that bezier curves autoscale to their curves, and not their
8094 # control points
8095 verts = [[-1, 0],
8096 [0, -1],
8097 [1, 0],
8098 [1, 0]]
8099 codes = [mpath.Path.MOVETO,
8100 mpath.Path.CURVE3,
8101 mpath.Path.CURVE3,
8102 mpath.Path.CLOSEPOLY]
8103 p = mpath.Path(verts, codes)
8104
8105 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
8106 ax.add_patch(mpatches.PathPatch(p))
8107 ax.autoscale()
8108 # Bottom ylim should be at the edge of the curve (-0.5), and not include
8109 # the control point (at -1)
8110 assert ax.get_ylim()[0] == -0.5

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_box_aspect ( )
7472def test_box_aspect():
7473 # Test if axes with box_aspect=1 has same dimensions
7474 # as axes with aspect equal and adjustable="box"
7475
7476 fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots()
7477 axtwin = ax1.twinx()
7478 axtwin.plot([12, 344])
7479
7480 ax1.set_box_aspect(1)
7481 assert ax1.get_box_aspect() == 1.0
7482
7483 fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots()
7484 ax2.margins(0)
7485 ax2.plot([0, 2], [6, 8])
7486 ax2.set_aspect("equal", adjustable="box")
7487
7488 fig1.canvas.draw()
7489 fig2.canvas.draw()
7490
7491 bb1 = ax1.get_position()
7492 bbt = axtwin.get_position()
7493 bb2 = ax2.get_position()
7494
7495 assert_array_equal(bb1.extents, bb2.extents)
7496 assert_array_equal(bbt.extents, bb2.extents)

3356def test_boxplot_marker_behavior():
3357 plt.rcParams['lines.marker'] = 's'
3358 plt.rcParams['boxplot.flierprops.marker'] = 'o'
3359 plt.rcParams['boxplot.meanprops.marker'] = '^'
3360 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
3361 test_data = np.arange(100)
3362 test_data[-1] = 150 # a flier point
3363 bxp_handle = ax.boxplot(test_data, showmeans=True)
3364 for bxp_lines in ['whiskers', 'caps', 'boxes', 'medians']:
3365 for each_line in bxp_handle[bxp_lines]:
3366 # Ensure that the rcParams['lines.marker'] is overridden by ''
3367 assert each_line.get_marker() == ''
3368
3369 # Ensure that markers for fliers and means aren't overridden with ''
3370 assert bxp_handle['fliers'][0].get_marker() == 'o'
3371 assert bxp_handle['means'][0].get_marker() == '^'
3372

◆ test_errorbar()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_errorbar ( )
3636def test_errorbar():
3637 # longdouble due to floating point rounding issues with certain
3638 # computer chipsets
3639 x = np.arange(0.1, 4, 0.5, dtype=np.longdouble)
3640 y = np.exp(-x)
3641
3642 yerr = 0.1 + 0.2*np.sqrt(x)
3643 xerr = 0.1 + yerr
3644
3645 # First illustrate basic pyplot interface, using defaults where possible.
3646 fig = plt.figure()
3647 ax = fig.gca()
3648 ax.errorbar(x, y, xerr=0.2, yerr=0.4)
3649 ax.set_title("Simplest errorbars, 0.2 in x, 0.4 in y")
3650
3651 # Now switch to a more OO interface to exercise more features.
3652 fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, sharex=True)
3653 ax = axs[0, 0]
3654 ax.errorbar(x, y, yerr=yerr, fmt='o')
3655 ax.set_title('Vert. symmetric')
3656
3657 # With 4 subplots, reduce the number of axis ticks to avoid crowding.
3658 ax.locator_params(nbins=4)
3659
3660 ax = axs[0, 1]
3661 ax.errorbar(x, y, xerr=xerr, fmt='o', alpha=0.4)
3662 ax.set_title('Hor. symmetric w/ alpha')
3663
3664 ax = axs[1, 0]
3665 ax.errorbar(x, y, yerr=[yerr, 2*yerr], xerr=[xerr, 2*xerr], fmt='--o')
3666 ax.set_title('H, V asymmetric')
3667
3668 ax = axs[1, 1]
3669 ax.set_yscale('log')
3670 # Here we have to be careful to keep all y values positive:
3671 ylower = np.maximum(1e-2, y - yerr)
3672 yerr_lower = y - ylower
3673
3674 ax.errorbar(x, y, yerr=[yerr_lower, 2*yerr], xerr=xerr,
3675 fmt='o', ecolor='g', capthick=2)
3676 ax.set_title('Mixed sym., log y')
3677 # Force limits due to floating point slop potentially expanding the range
3678 ax.set_ylim(1e-2, 1e1)
3679
3680 fig.suptitle('Variable errorbars')
3681
3682 # Reuse the first testcase from above for a labeled data test
3683 data = {"x": x, "y": y}
3684 fig = plt.figure()
3685 ax = fig.gca()
3686 ax.errorbar("x", "y", xerr=0.2, yerr=0.4, data=data)
3687 ax.set_title("Simplest errorbars, 0.2 in x, 0.4 in y")
3688
3689

◆ test_errorbar_every()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_errorbar_every (   fig_test,
  fig_ref 
)
3873def test_errorbar_every(fig_test, fig_ref):
3874 x = np.linspace(0, 1, 15)
3875 y = x * (1-x)
3876 yerr = y/6
3877
3878 ax_ref = fig_ref.subplots()
3879 ax_test = fig_test.subplots()
3880
3881 for color, shift in zip('rgbk', [0, 0, 2, 7]):
3882 y += .02
3883
3884 # Check errorevery using an explicit offset and step.
3885 ax_test.errorbar(x, y, yerr, errorevery=(shift, 4),
3886 capsize=4, c=color)
3887
3888 # Using manual errorbars
3889 # n.b. errorbar draws the main plot at z=2.1 by default
3890 ax_ref.plot(x, y, c=color, zorder=2.1)
3891 ax_ref.errorbar(x[shift::4], y[shift::4], yerr[shift::4],
3892 capsize=4, c=color, fmt='none')
3893
3894 # Check that markevery is propagated to line, without affecting errorbars.
3895 ax_test.errorbar(x, y + 0.1, yerr, markevery=(1, 4), capsize=4, fmt='o')
3896 ax_ref.plot(x[1::4], y[1::4] + 0.1, 'o', zorder=2.1)
3897 ax_ref.errorbar(x, y + 0.1, yerr, capsize=4, fmt='none')
3898
3899 # Check that passing a slice to markevery/errorevery works.
3900 ax_test.errorbar(x, y + 0.2, yerr, errorevery=slice(2, None, 3),
3901 markevery=slice(2, None, 3),

◆ test_errorbar_limits()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_errorbar_limits ( )
3739def test_errorbar_limits():
3740 x = np.arange(0.5, 5.5, 0.5)
3741 y = np.exp(-x)
3742 xerr = 0.1
3743 yerr = 0.2
3744 ls = 'dotted'
3745
3746 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
3747
3748 # standard error bars
3749 ax.errorbar(x, y, xerr=xerr, yerr=yerr, ls=ls, color='blue')
3750
3751 # including upper limits
3752 uplims = np.zeros_like(x)
3753 uplims[[1, 5, 9]] = True
3754 ax.errorbar(x, y+0.5, xerr=xerr, yerr=yerr, uplims=uplims, ls=ls,
3755 color='green')
3756
3757 # including lower limits
3758 lolims = np.zeros_like(x)
3759 lolims[[2, 4, 8]] = True
3760 ax.errorbar(x, y+1.0, xerr=xerr, yerr=yerr, lolims=lolims, ls=ls,
3761 color='red')
3762
3763 # including upper and lower limits
3764 ax.errorbar(x, y+1.5, marker='o', ms=8, xerr=xerr, yerr=yerr,
3765 lolims=lolims, uplims=uplims, ls=ls, color='magenta')
3766
3767 # including xlower and xupper limits
3768 xerr = 0.2
3769 yerr = np.full_like(x, 0.2)
3770 yerr[[3, 6]] = 0.3
3771 xlolims = lolims
3772 xuplims = uplims
3773 lolims = np.zeros_like(x)
3774 uplims = np.zeros_like(x)
3775 lolims[[6]] = True
3776 uplims[[3]] = True
3777 ax.errorbar(x, y+2.1, marker='o', ms=8, xerr=xerr, yerr=yerr,
3778 xlolims=xlolims, xuplims=xuplims, uplims=uplims,
3779 lolims=lolims, ls='none', mec='blue', capsize=0,
3780 color='cyan')
3781 ax.set_xlim((0, 5.5))
3782 ax.set_title('Errorbar upper and lower limits')
3783
3784

Test the *colors* parameter of eventplot. Inspired by issue #8193.
4506def test_eventplot_colors(colors):
4507 """Test the *colors* parameter of eventplot. Inspired by issue #8193."""
4508 data = [[0], [1], [2], [3]] # 4 successive events of different nature
4509
4510 # Build the list of the expected colors
4511 expected = [c if c is not None else 'C0' for c in colors]
4512 # Convert the list into an array of RGBA values
4513 # NB: ['rgbk'] is not a valid argument for to_rgba_array, while 'rgbk' is.
4514 if len(expected) == 1:
4515 expected = expected[0]
4516 expected = np.broadcast_to(mcolors.to_rgba_array(expected), (len(data), 4))
4517
4518 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
4519 if len(colors) == 1: # tuple with a single string (like '0.5' or 'rgbk')
4520 colors = colors[0]
4521 collections = ax.eventplot(data, colors=colors)
4522
4523 for coll, color in zip(collections, expected):
4524 assert_allclose(coll.get_color(), color)

1997def test_hist_log_2(fig_test, fig_ref):

2078def test_hist_unequal_bins_density():
2079 # Test correct behavior of normalized histogram with unequal bins
2080 # https://github.com/matplotlib/matplotlib/issues/9557
2081 rng = np.random.RandomState(57483)
2082 t = rng.randn(100)
2083 bins = [-3, -1, -0.5, 0, 1, 5]
2084 mpl_heights, _, _ = plt.hist(t, bins=bins, density=True)
2085 np_heights, _ = np.histogram(t, bins=bins, density=True)
2086 assert_allclose(mpl_heights, np_heights)

4797def test_hlines():
4798 # normal
4799 y1 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 7]
4800 x1 = [2, -6, 3, 8, 2]
4801 fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots()
4802 ax1.hlines(y1, 0, x1, colors='g', linewidth=5)
4803
4804 # GH #7406
4805 y2 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
4806 x2 = [2, -6, 3, 8, np.nan, 2]
4807 fig2, (ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(nrows=3, figsize=(4, 8))
4808 ax2.hlines(y2, 0, x2, colors='g', linewidth=5)
4809
4810 y3 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
4811 x3 = [np.nan, 2, -6, 3, 8, 2]
4812 ax3.hlines(y3, 0, x3, colors='r', linewidth=3, linestyle='--')
4813
4814 y4 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
4815 x4 = [np.nan, 2, -6, 3, 8, np.nan]
4816 ax4.hlines(y4, 0, x4, colors='k', linewidth=2)
4817
4818 # tweak the y-axis so we can see the lines better
4819 for ax in [ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4]:
4820 ax.set_ylim(0, 10)
4821
4822 # check that the x-lims are all automatically the same
4823 assert ax1.get_xlim() == ax2.get_xlim()
4824 assert ax1.get_xlim() == ax3.get_xlim()
4825 assert ax1.get_xlim() == ax4.get_xlim()
4826
4827 fig3, ax5 = plt.subplots()
4828 y5 = np.ma.masked_equal([2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12], 8)
4829 xmin5 = np.ma.masked_equal([0, 1, -1, 0, 2, 1], 2)
4830 xmax5 = np.ma.masked_equal([13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18], 18)
4831 ax5.hlines(y5, xmin5, xmax5, colors='k', linewidth=2)
4832 ax5.set_ylim(0, 15)

◆ test_imshow_clip()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_imshow_clip ( )
1035def test_imshow_clip():
1036 # As originally reported by Gellule Xg <gellule.xg@free.fr>
1037 # use former defaults to match existing baseline image
1038 matplotlib.rcParams['image.interpolation'] = 'nearest'
1039
1040 # Create a NxN image
1041 N = 100
1042 (x, y) = np.indices((N, N))
1043 x -= N//2
1044 y -= N//2
1045 r = np.sqrt(x**2+y**2-x*y)
1046
1047 # Create a contour plot at N/4 and extract both the clip path and transform
1048 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1049
1050 c = ax.contour(r, [N/4])
1051 x = c.collections[0]
1052 clip_path = x.get_paths()[0]
1053 clip_transform = x.get_transform()
1054
1055 clip_path = mtransforms.TransformedPath(clip_path, clip_transform)
1056
1057 # Plot the image clipped by the contour
1058 ax.imshow(r, clip_path=clip_path)
1059

  y_inverted 
) 
Test that the inset lines are correctly located with inverted data axes.
6980def test_indicate_inset_inverted(x_inverted, y_inverted):
6981 """
6982 Test that the inset lines are correctly located with inverted data axes.
6983 """
6984 fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2)
6985
6986 x = np.arange(10)
6987 ax1.plot(x, x, 'o')
6988 if x_inverted:
6989 ax1.invert_xaxis()
6990 if y_inverted:
6991 ax1.invert_yaxis()
6992
6993 rect, bounds = ax1.indicate_inset([2, 2, 5, 4], ax2)
6994 lower_left, upper_left, lower_right, upper_right = bounds
6995
6996 sign_x = -1 if x_inverted else 1
6997 sign_y = -1 if y_inverted else 1
6998 assert sign_x * (lower_right.xy2[0] - lower_left.xy2[0]) > 0
6999 assert sign_x * (upper_right.xy2[0] - upper_left.xy2[0]) > 0
7000 assert sign_y * (upper_left.xy2[1] - lower_left.xy2[1]) > 0
7001 assert sign_y * (upper_right.xy2[1] - lower_right.xy2[1]) > 0
7002
7003

6891def test_inset():
6892 """
6893 Ensure that inset_ax argument is indeed optional
6894 """
6895 dx, dy = 0.05, 0.05
6896 # generate 2 2d grids for the x & y bounds
6897 y, x = np.mgrid[slice(1, 5 + dy, dy),
6898 slice(1, 5 + dx, dx)]
6899 z = np.sin(x) ** 10 + np.cos(10 + y * x) * np.cos(x)
6900
6901 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
6902 ax.pcolormesh(x, y, z[:-1, :-1])
6903 ax.set_aspect(1.)
6904 ax.apply_aspect()
6905 # we need to apply_aspect to make the drawing below work.
6906
6907 xlim = [1.5, 2.15]
6908 ylim = [2, 2.5]
6909
6910 rect = [xlim[0], ylim[0], xlim[1] - xlim[0], ylim[1] - ylim[0]]
6911
6912 rec, connectors = ax.indicate_inset(bounds=rect)
6913 assert connectors is None
6914 fig.canvas.draw()
6915 xx = np.array([[1.5, 2.],
6916 [2.15, 2.5]])
6917 assert np.all(rec.get_bbox().get_points() == xx)

6816 with pytest.raises(ValueError):
6817 plt.ylim(np.nan)
6818 with pytest.raises(ValueError):
6819 plt.ylim(np.inf)

6823@pytest.mark.parametrize('xscale', ['symlog', 'log'])
6824@pytest.mark.parametrize('yscale', ['symlog', 'log'])

◆ test_inverted_cla()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_inverted_cla ( )
437def test_inverted_cla():
438 # GitHub PR #5450. Setting autoscale should reset
439 # axes to be non-inverted.
440 # plotting an image, then 1d graph, axis is now down
441 fig = plt.figure(0)
442 ax = fig.gca()
443 # 1. test that a new axis is not inverted per default
444 assert not ax.xaxis_inverted()
445 assert not ax.yaxis_inverted()
446 img = np.random.random((100, 100))
447 ax.imshow(img)
448 # 2. test that a image axis is inverted
449 assert not ax.xaxis_inverted()
450 assert ax.yaxis_inverted()
451 # 3. test that clearing and plotting a line, axes are
452 # not inverted
453 ax.cla()
454 x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
455 ax.plot(x, np.cos(x))
456 assert not ax.xaxis_inverted()
457 assert not ax.yaxis_inverted()
458
459 # 4. autoscaling should not bring back axes to normal
460 ax.cla()
461 ax.imshow(img)
462 plt.autoscale()
463 assert not ax.xaxis_inverted()
464 assert ax.yaxis_inverted()
465
466 for ax in fig.axes:
467 ax.remove()
468 # 5. two shared axes. Inverting the leader axis should invert the shared
469 # axes; clearing the leader axis should bring axes in shared
470 # axes back to normal.
471 ax0 = plt.subplot(211)
472 ax1 = plt.subplot(212, sharey=ax0)
473 ax0.yaxis.set_inverted(True)
474 assert ax1.yaxis_inverted()
475 ax1.plot(x, np.cos(x))
476 ax0.cla()
477 assert not ax1.yaxis_inverted()
478 ax1.cla()
479 # 6. clearing the follower should not touch limits
480 ax0.imshow(img)
481 ax1.plot(x, np.cos(x))
482 ax1.cla()
483 assert ax.yaxis_inverted()
484
485 # clean up
486 plt.close(fig)
487
488

6768def test_log_margins():
6769 plt.rcParams['axes.autolimit_mode'] = 'data'
6770 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
6771 margin = 0.05
6772 ax.set_xmargin(margin)
6773 ax.semilogx([10, 100], [10, 100])
6774 xlim0, xlim1 = ax.get_xlim()
6775 transform = ax.xaxis.get_transform()
6776 xlim0t, xlim1t = transform.transform([xlim0, xlim1])
6777 x0t, x1t = transform.transform([10, 100])
6778 delta = (x1t - x0t) * margin
6779 assert_allclose([xlim0t + delta, xlim1t - delta], [x0t, x1t])

◆ test_margins()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_margins ( )
5797def test_margins():
5798 # test all ways margins can be called
5799 data = [1, 10]
5800 xmin = 0.0
5801 xmax = len(data) - 1.0
5802 ymin = min(data)
5803 ymax = max(data)
5804
5805 fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 1)
5806 ax1.plot(data)
5807 ax1.margins(1)
5808 assert ax1.margins() == (1, 1)
5809 assert ax1.get_xlim() == (xmin - (xmax - xmin) * 1,
5810 xmax + (xmax - xmin) * 1)
5811 assert ax1.get_ylim() == (ymin - (ymax - ymin) * 1,
5812 ymax + (ymax - ymin) * 1)
5813
5814 fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots(1, 1)
5815 ax2.plot(data)
5816 ax2.margins(0.5, 2)
5817 assert ax2.margins() == (0.5, 2)
5818 assert ax2.get_xlim() == (xmin - (xmax - xmin) * 0.5,
5819 xmax + (xmax - xmin) * 0.5)
5820 assert ax2.get_ylim() == (ymin - (ymax - ymin) * 2,
5821 ymax + (ymax - ymin) * 2)
5822
5823 fig3, ax3 = plt.subplots(1, 1)
5824 ax3.plot(data)
5825 ax3.margins(x=-0.2, y=0.5)
5826 assert ax3.margins() == (-0.2, 0.5)
5827 assert ax3.get_xlim() == (xmin - (xmax - xmin) * -0.2,
5828 xmax + (xmax - xmin) * -0.2)
5829 assert ax3.get_ylim() == (ymin - (ymax - ymin) * 0.5,
5830 ymax + (ymax - ymin) * 0.5)
5831

1565def test_markevery_linear_scales():
1566 cases = [None,
1567 8,
1568 (30, 8),
1569 [16, 24, 30], [0, -1],
1570 slice(100, 200, 3),
1571 0.1, 0.3, 1.5,
1572 (0.0, 0.1), (0.45, 0.1)]
1573
1574 cols = 3
1575 gs = matplotlib.gridspec.GridSpec(len(cases) // cols + 1, cols)

4891def test_mixed_collection():
4892 # First illustrate basic pyplot interface, using defaults where possible.
4893 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
4894
4895 c = mpatches.Circle((8, 8), radius=4, facecolor='none', edgecolor='green')
4896
4897 # PDF can optimize this one
4898 p1 = mpl.collections.PatchCollection([c], match_original=True)
4899 p1.set_offsets([[0, 0], [24, 24]])
4900 p1.set_linewidths([1, 5])
4901
4902 # PDF can't optimize this one, because the alpha of the edge changes
4903 p2 = mpl.collections.PatchCollection([c], match_original=True)
4904 p2.set_offsets([[48, 0], [-32, -16]])
4905 p2.set_linewidths([1, 5])
4906 p2.set_edgecolors([[0, 0, 0.1, 1.0], [0, 0, 0.1, 0.5]])
4907
4908 ax.patch.set_color('0.5')
4909 ax.add_collection(p1)
4910 ax.add_collection(p2)
4911
4912 ax.set_xlim(0, 16)
4913 ax.set_ylim(0, 16)
4914

◆ test_mollweide_forward_inverse_closure()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_mollweide_forward_inverse_closure ( )
4367def test_mollweide_forward_inverse_closure():
4368 # test that the round-trip Mollweide forward->inverse transformation is an
4369 # approximate identity
4370 fig = plt.figure()
4371 ax = fig.add_subplot(projection='mollweide')
4372
4373 # set up 1-degree grid in longitude, latitude
4374 lon = np.linspace(-np.pi, np.pi, 360)
4375 lat = np.linspace(-np.pi / 2.0, np.pi / 2.0, 180)
4376 lon, lat = np.meshgrid(lon, lat)
4377 ll = np.vstack((lon.flatten(), lat.flatten())).T
4378
4379 # perform forward transform
4380 xy = ax.transProjection.transform(ll)
4381
4382 # perform inverse transform
4383 ll2 = ax.transProjection.inverted().transform(xy)
4384
4385 # compare
4386 np.testing.assert_array_almost_equal(ll, ll2, 3)
4387
4388

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_mollweide_inverse_forward_closure ( )
4389def test_mollweide_inverse_forward_closure():
4390 # test that the round-trip Mollweide inverse->forward transformation is an
4391 # approximate identity
4392 fig = plt.figure()
4393 ax = fig.add_subplot(projection='mollweide')
4394
4395 # set up grid in x, y
4396 x = np.linspace(0, 1, 500)
4397 x, y = np.meshgrid(x, x)
4398 xy = np.vstack((x.flatten(), y.flatten())).T
4399
4400 # perform inverse transform
4401 ll = ax.transProjection.inverted().transform(xy)
4402
4403 # perform forward transform
4404 xy2 = ax.transProjection.transform(ll)
4405
4406 # compare
4407 np.testing.assert_array_almost_equal(xy, xy2, 3)

1353def test_pcolorargs():
1354 n = 12
1355 x = np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, n)
1356 y = np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, n*2)
1357 X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
1358 Z = np.hypot(X, Y) / 5
1359
1360 _, ax = plt.subplots()
1361 with pytest.raises(TypeError):
1362 ax.pcolormesh(y, x, Z)
1363 with pytest.raises(TypeError):
1364 ax.pcolormesh(X, Y, Z.T)
1365 with pytest.raises(TypeError):
1366 ax.pcolormesh(x, y, Z[:-1, :-1], shading="gouraud")
1367 with pytest.raises(TypeError):
1368 ax.pcolormesh(X, Y, Z[:-1, :-1], shading="gouraud")
1369 x[0] = np.NaN
1370 with pytest.raises(ValueError):
1371 ax.pcolormesh(x, y, Z[:-1, :-1])
1372 with np.errstate(invalid='ignore'):
1373 x = np.ma.array(x, mask=(x < 0))
1374 with pytest.raises(ValueError):
1375 ax.pcolormesh(x, y, Z[:-1, :-1])
1376 # Expect a warning with non-increasing coordinates
1377 x = [359, 0, 1]
1378 y = [-10, 10]
1379 X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
1380 Z = np.zeros(X.shape)
1381 with pytest.warns(UserWarning,
1382 match='are not monotonically increasing or decreasing'):
1383 ax.pcolormesh(X, Y, Z, shading='auto')

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_pcolormesh ( )
1221def test_pcolormesh():
1222 # Remove this line when this test image is regenerated.
1223 plt.rcParams['pcolormesh.snap'] = False
1224
1225 n = 12
1226 x = np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, n)
1227 y = np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, n*2)
1228 X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)
1229 Qx = np.cos(Y) - np.cos(X)
1230 Qz = np.sin(Y) + np.sin(X)
1231 Qx = (Qx + 1.1)
1232 Z = np.hypot(X, Y) / 5
1233 Z = (Z - Z.min()) / Z.ptp()
1234
1235 # The color array can include masked values:
1236 Zm = ma.masked_where(np.abs(Qz) < 0.5 * np.max(Qz), Z)
1237
1238 fig, (ax1, ax2, ax3) = plt.subplots(1, 3)
1239 ax1.pcolormesh(Qx, Qz, Z[:-1, :-1], lw=0.5, edgecolors='k')
1240 ax2.pcolormesh(Qx, Qz, Z[:-1, :-1], lw=2, edgecolors=['b', 'w'])
1241 ax3.pcolormesh(Qx, Qz, Z, shading="gouraud")

◆ test_pcolormesh_alpha()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_pcolormesh_alpha ( )
1267def test_pcolormesh_alpha():
1268 # Remove this line when this test image is regenerated.
1269 plt.rcParams['pcolormesh.snap'] = False
1270
1271 n = 12
1272 X, Y = np.meshgrid(
1273 np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, n),
1274 np.linspace(-1.5, 1.5, n*2)
1275 )
1276 Qx = X
1277 Qy = Y + np.sin(X)
1278 Z = np.hypot(X, Y) / 5
1279 Z = (Z - Z.min()) / Z.ptp()
1280 vir = mpl.colormaps["viridis"].resampled(16)
1281 # make another colormap with varying alpha
1282 colors = vir(np.arange(16))
1283 colors[:, 3] = 0.5 + 0.5*np.sin(np.arange(16))
1284 cmap = mcolors.ListedColormap(colors)
1285
1286 fig, ((ax1, ax2), (ax3, ax4)) = plt.subplots(2, 2)
1287 for ax in ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4:
1288 ax.add_patch(mpatches.Rectangle(
1289 (0, -1.5), 1.5, 3, facecolor=[.7, .1, .1, .5], zorder=0
1290 ))
1291 # ax1, ax2: constant alpha
1292 ax1.pcolormesh(Qx, Qy, Z[:-1, :-1], cmap=vir, alpha=0.4,
1293 shading='flat', zorder=1)
1294 ax2.pcolormesh(Qx, Qy, Z, cmap=vir, alpha=0.4, shading='gouraud', zorder=1)
1295 # ax3, ax4: alpha from colormap
1296 ax3.pcolormesh(Qx, Qy, Z[:-1, :-1], cmap=cmap, shading='flat', zorder=1)
1297 ax4.pcolormesh(Qx, Qy, Z, cmap=cmap, shading='gouraud', zorder=1)
1298

◆ test_psd_csd()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_psd_csd ( )
5070def test_psd_csd():
5071 n = 10000
5072 Fs = 100.
5073
5074 fstims = [[Fs/4, Fs/5, Fs/11], [Fs/4.7, Fs/5.6, Fs/11.9]]
5075 NFFT_freqs = int(1000 * Fs / np.min(fstims))
5076 x = np.arange(0, n, 1/Fs)
5077 ys_freqs = np.sin(2 * np.pi * np.multiply.outer(fstims, x)).sum(axis=1)
5078
5079 NFFT_noise = int(1000 * Fs / 11)
5080 np.random.seed(0)
5081 ys_noise = [np.random.standard_normal(n), np.random.rand(n)]
5082
5083 all_kwargs = [{"sides": "default"},
5084 {"sides": "onesided", "return_line": False},
5085 {"sides": "twosided", "return_line": True}]
5086 for ys, NFFT in [(ys_freqs, NFFT_freqs), (ys_noise, NFFT_noise)]:
5087 noverlap = NFFT // 2
5088 pad_to = int(2 ** np.ceil(np.log2(NFFT)))
5089 for ax, kwargs in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_kwargs):
5090 ret = ax.psd(np.concatenate(ys), NFFT=NFFT, Fs=Fs,
5091 noverlap=noverlap, pad_to=pad_to, **kwargs)
5092 assert len(ret) == 2 + kwargs.get("return_line", False)
5093 ax.set(xlabel="", ylabel="")
5094 for ax, kwargs in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_kwargs):
5095 ret = ax.csd(*ys, NFFT=NFFT, Fs=Fs,
5096 noverlap=noverlap, pad_to=pad_to, **kwargs)
5097 assert len(ret) == 2 + kwargs.get("return_line", False)
5098 ax.set(xlabel="", ylabel="")
5099
5100

◆ test_reset_ticks()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_reset_ticks (   fig_test,

5289def test_reset_ticks(fig_test, fig_ref):
5290 for fig in [fig_ref, fig_test]:
5291 ax = fig.add_subplot()
5292 ax.grid(True)
5293 ax.tick_params(
5294 direction='in', length=10, width=5, color='C0', pad=12,
5295 labelsize=14, labelcolor='C1', labelrotation=45,
5296 grid_color='C2', grid_alpha=0.8, grid_linewidth=3,
5297 grid_linestyle='--')
5298 fig.draw_without_rendering()
5299
5300 # After we've changed any setting on ticks, reset_ticks will mean
5301 # re-creating them from scratch. This *should* appear the same as not
5302 # resetting them.
5303 for ax in fig_test.axes:
5304 ax.xaxis.reset_ticks()

◆ test_shared_with_aspect_3()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_shared_with_aspect_3 ( )
5368def test_shared_with_aspect_3():
5369 # Different aspect ratios:
5370 for adjustable in ['box', 'datalim']:
5371 fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharey=True)
5372 axs[0].set_aspect(2, adjustable=adjustable)
5373 axs[1].set_aspect(0.5, adjustable=adjustable)
5374 axs[0].plot([1, 2], [3, 4])
5375 axs[1].plot([3, 4], [1, 2])
5376 plt.draw() # Trigger apply_aspect().
5377 assert axs[0].get_xlim() != axs[1].get_xlim()
5378 assert axs[0].get_ylim() == axs[1].get_ylim()
5379 fig_aspect = fig.bbox_inches.height / fig.bbox_inches.width
5380 for ax in axs:
5381 p = ax.get_position()
5382 box_aspect = p.height / p.width
5383 lim_aspect = ax.viewLim.height / ax.viewLim.width
5384 expected = fig_aspect * box_aspect / lim_aspect
5385 assert round(expected, 4) == round(ax.get_aspect(), 4)
5386
5387

4926def test_specgram():
4927 """Test axes.specgram in default (psd) mode."""
4928
4929 # use former defaults to match existing baseline image
4930 matplotlib.rcParams['image.interpolation'] = 'nearest'
4931
4932 n = 1000
4933 Fs = 10.
4934
4935 fstims = [[Fs/4, Fs/5, Fs/11], [Fs/4.7, Fs/5.6, Fs/11.9]]
4936 NFFT_freqs = int(10 * Fs / np.min(fstims))
4937 x = np.arange(0, n, 1/Fs)
4938 y_freqs = np.concatenate(
4939 np.sin(2 * np.pi * np.multiply.outer(fstims, x)).sum(axis=1))
4940
4941 NFFT_noise = int(10 * Fs / 11)
4942 np.random.seed(0)
4943 y_noise = np.concatenate([np.random.standard_normal(n), np.random.rand(n)])
4944
4945 all_sides = ["default", "onesided", "twosided"]
4946 for y, NFFT in [(y_freqs, NFFT_freqs), (y_noise, NFFT_noise)]:
4947 noverlap = NFFT // 2
4948 pad_to = int(2 ** np.ceil(np.log2(NFFT)))
4949 for ax, sides in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_sides):
4950 ax.specgram(y, NFFT=NFFT, Fs=Fs, noverlap=noverlap,
4951 pad_to=pad_to, sides=sides)
4952 for ax, sides in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_sides):
4953 ax.specgram(y, NFFT=NFFT, Fs=Fs, noverlap=noverlap,
4954 pad_to=pad_to, sides=sides,
4955 scale="linear", norm=matplotlib.colors.LogNorm())

5111def test_spectrum():
5112 n = 10000
5113 Fs = 100.
5114
5115 fstims1 = [Fs/4, Fs/5, Fs/11]
5116 NFFT = int(1000 * Fs / min(fstims1))
5117 pad_to = int(2 ** np.ceil(np.log2(NFFT)))
5118
5119 x = np.arange(0, n, 1/Fs)
5120 y_freqs = ((np.sin(2 * np.pi * np.outer(x, fstims1)) * 10**np.arange(3))
5121 .sum(axis=1))
5122 np.random.seed(0)
5123 y_noise = np.hstack([np.random.standard_normal(n), np.random.rand(n)]) - .5
5124
5125 all_sides = ["default", "onesided", "twosided"]
5126 kwargs = {"Fs": Fs, "pad_to": pad_to}
5127 for y in [y_freqs, y_noise]:
5128 for ax, sides in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_sides):
5129 spec, freqs, line = ax.magnitude_spectrum(y, sides=sides, **kwargs)
5130 ax.set(xlabel="", ylabel="")
5131 for ax, sides in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_sides):
5132 spec, freqs, line = ax.magnitude_spectrum(y, sides=sides, **kwargs,
5133 scale="dB")
5134 ax.set(xlabel="", ylabel="")
5135 for ax, sides in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_sides):
5136 spec, freqs, line = ax.angle_spectrum(y, sides=sides, **kwargs)
5137 ax.set(xlabel="", ylabel="")
5138 for ax, sides in zip(plt.figure().subplots(3), all_sides):
5139 spec, freqs, line = ax.phase_spectrum(y, sides=sides, **kwargs)
5140 ax.set(xlabel="", ylabel="")

◆ test_stackplot_baseline()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_stackplot_baseline ( )
2870def test_stackplot_baseline():
2871 np.random.seed(0)
2872
2873 def layers(n, m):
2874 a = np.zeros((m, n))
2875 for i in range(n):
2876 for j in range(5):
2877 x = 1 / (.1 + np.random.random())
2878 y = 2 * np.random.random() - .5
2879 z = 10 / (.1 + np.random.random())
2880 a[:, i] += x * np.exp(-((np.arange(m) / m - y) * z) ** 2)
2881 return a
2882
2883 d = layers(3, 100)
2884 d[50, :] = 0 # test for fixed weighted wiggle (issue #6313)
2885
2886 fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2)
2887
2888 axs[0, 0].stackplot(range(100), d.T, baseline='zero')
2889 axs[0, 1].stackplot(range(100), d.T, baseline='sym')
2890 axs[1, 0].stackplot(range(100), d.T, baseline='wiggle')
2891 axs[1, 1].stackplot(range(100), d.T, baseline='weighted_wiggle')

◆ test_stem_markerfmt()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_stem_markerfmt ( ) 
Test that stem(..., markerfmt=...) produces the intended markers.
4031def test_stem_markerfmt():
4032 """Test that stem(..., markerfmt=...) produces the intended markers."""
4033 def _assert_equal(stem_container, linecolor=None, markercolor=None,
4034 marker=None):
4035 """
4036 Check that the given StemContainer has the properties listed as
4037 keyword-arguments.
4038 """
4039 if linecolor is not None:
4040 assert mcolors.same_color(
4041 stem_container.stemlines.get_color(),
4042 linecolor)
4043 if markercolor is not None:
4044 assert mcolors.same_color(
4045 stem_container.markerline.get_color(),
4046 markercolor)
4047 if marker is not None:
4048 assert stem_container.markerline.get_marker() == marker
4049 assert stem_container.markerline.get_linestyle() == 'None'
4050
4051 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
4052
4053 x = [1, 3, 5]
4054 y = [9, 8, 7]
4055
4056 # no linefmt
4057 _assert_equal(ax.stem(x, y), markercolor='C0', marker='o')
4058 _assert_equal(ax.stem(x, y, markerfmt='x'), markercolor='C0', marker='x')
4059 _assert_equal(ax.stem(x, y, markerfmt='rx'), markercolor='r', marker='x')
4060
4061 # positional linefmt
4062 _assert_equal(
4063 ax.stem(x, y, 'r'), # marker color follows linefmt if not given
4064 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='o')
4065 _assert_equal(
4066 ax.stem(x, y, 'rx'), # the marker is currently not taken from linefmt
4067 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='o')
4068 _assert_equal(
4069 ax.stem(x, y, 'r', markerfmt='x'), # only marker type specified
4070 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='x')
4071 _assert_equal(
4072 ax.stem(x, y, 'r', markerfmt='g'), # only marker color specified
4073 linecolor='r', markercolor='g', marker='o')
4074 _assert_equal(
4075 ax.stem(x, y, 'r', markerfmt='gx'), # marker type and color specified
4076 linecolor='r', markercolor='g', marker='x')
4077 _assert_equal(
4078 ax.stem(x, y, 'r', markerfmt=' '), # markerfmt=' ' for no marker
4079 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='None')
4080 _assert_equal(
4081 ax.stem(x, y, 'r', markerfmt=''), # markerfmt='' for no marker
4082 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='None')
4083
4084 # with linefmt kwarg
4085 _assert_equal(
4086 ax.stem(x, y, linefmt='r'),
4087 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='o')
4088 _assert_equal(
4089 ax.stem(x, y, linefmt='r', markerfmt='x'),
4090 linecolor='r', markercolor='r', marker='x')
4091 _assert_equal(
4092 ax.stem(x, y, linefmt='r', markerfmt='gx'),
4093 linecolor='r', markercolor='g', marker='x')
4094
4095

◆ test_subclass_clear_cla()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_subclass_clear_cla ( )
489def test_subclass_clear_cla():
490 # Ensure that subclasses of Axes call cla/clear correctly.
491 # Note, we cannot use mocking here as we want to be sure that the
492 # superclass fallback does not recurse.
493
494 with pytest.warns(PendingDeprecationWarning,
495 match='Overriding `Axes.cla`'):
496 class ClaAxes(Axes):
497 def cla(self):
498 nonlocal called
499 called = True
500
501 with pytest.warns(PendingDeprecationWarning,
502 match='Overriding `Axes.cla`'):
503 class ClaSuperAxes(Axes):
504 def cla(self):
505 nonlocal called
506 called = True
507 super().cla()
508
509 class SubClaAxes(ClaAxes):
510 pass
511
512 class ClearAxes(Axes):
513 def clear(self):
514 nonlocal called
515 called = True
516
517 class ClearSuperAxes(Axes):
518 def clear(self):
519 nonlocal called
520 called = True
521 super().clear()
522
523 class SubClearAxes(ClearAxes):
524 pass
525
526 fig = Figure()
527 for axes_class in [ClaAxes, ClaSuperAxes, SubClaAxes,
528 ClearAxes, ClearSuperAxes, SubClearAxes]:
529 called = False
530 ax = axes_class(fig, [0, 0, 1, 1])
531 # Axes.__init__ has already called clear (which aliases to cla or is in
532 # the subclass).
533 assert called
534
535 called = False
536 ax.cla()
537 assert called
538
539

6640def test_title_above_offset(left, center):
6641 # Test that title moves if overlaps with yaxis offset text.
6642 mpl.rcParams['axes.titley'] = None
6643 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
6644 ax.set_ylim(1e11)
6645 ax.set_title(left, loc='left')
6646 ax.set_title(center)
6647 fig.draw_without_rendering()
6648 if left and not center:

6650 elif not left and center:

6652 else:
6653 yleft = ax._left_title.get_position()[1]
6654 ycenter = ax.title.get_position()[1]
6655 assert yleft > 1.0
6656 assert ycenter == yleft

6145def test_title_pad():
6146 # check that title padding puts the title in the right
6147 # place...
6148 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
6149 ax.set_title('aardvark', pad=30.)
6150 m = ax.titleOffsetTrans.get_matrix()
6151 assert m[1, -1] == (30. / 72. * fig.dpi)

6158 assert m[1, -1] == (matplotlib.rcParams['axes.titlepad'] / 72. * fig.dpi)

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_twin_spines ( )
5169def test_twin_spines():
5170
5171 def make_patch_spines_invisible(ax):
5172 ax.set_frame_on(True)
5173 ax.patch.set_visible(False)
5174 ax.spines[:].set_visible(False)
5175
5176 fig = plt.figure(figsize=(4, 3))
5177 fig.subplots_adjust(right=0.75)
5178
5179 host = fig.add_subplot()
5180 par1 = host.twinx()
5181 par2 = host.twinx()
5182
5183 # Offset the right spine of par2. The ticks and label have already been
5184 # placed on the right by twinx above.
5185 par2.spines.right.set_position(("axes", 1.2))
5186 # Having been created by twinx, par2 has its frame off, so the line of
5187 # its detached spine is invisible. First, activate the frame but make
5188 # the patch and spines invisible.
5189 make_patch_spines_invisible(par2)
5190 # Second, show the right spine.
5191 par2.spines.right.set_visible(True)
5192
5193 p1, = host.plot([0, 1, 2], [0, 1, 2], "b-")
5194 p2, = par1.plot([0, 1, 2], [0, 3, 2], "r-")
5195 p3, = par2.plot([0, 1, 2], [50, 30, 15], "g-")
5196
5197 host.set_xlim(0, 2)
5198 host.set_ylim(0, 2)
5199 par1.set_ylim(0, 4)
5200 par2.set_ylim(1, 65)
5201
5202 host.yaxis.label.set_color(p1.get_color())
5203 par1.yaxis.label.set_color(p2.get_color())
5204 par2.yaxis.label.set_color(p3.get_color())
5205
5206 tkw = dict(size=4, width=1.5)
5207 host.tick_params(axis='y', colors=p1.get_color(), **tkw)
5208 par1.tick_params(axis='y', colors=p2.get_color(), **tkw)
5209 par2.tick_params(axis='y', colors=p3.get_color(), **tkw)
5210 host.tick_params(axis='x', **tkw)
5211

7570def test_unautoscale(axis, auto):

7572 x = np.arange(100)

7575

7577 set_lim = getattr(ax, f'set_{axis}lim')
7578 get_lim = getattr(ax, f'get_{axis}lim')

7581

611def test_use_sticky_edges():
612 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
613 ax.imshow([[0, 1], [2, 3]], origin='lower')
614 assert_allclose(ax.get_xlim(), (-0.5, 1.5))
615 assert_allclose(ax.get_ylim(), (-0.5, 1.5))
616 ax.use_sticky_edges = False
617 ax.autoscale()
618 xlim = (-0.5 - 2 * ax._xmargin, 1.5 + 2 * ax._xmargin)
619 ylim = (-0.5 - 2 * ax._ymargin, 1.5 + 2 * ax._ymargin)
620 assert_allclose(ax.get_xlim(), xlim)
621 assert_allclose(ax.get_ylim(), ylim)
622 # Make sure it is reversible:

624 ax.autoscale()

4750def test_vlines():
4751 # normal
4752 x1 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 7]
4753 y1 = [2, -6, 3, 8, 2]
4754 fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots()
4755 ax1.vlines(x1, 0, y1, colors='g', linewidth=5)
4756
4757 # GH #7406
4758 x2 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
4759 y2 = [2, -6, 3, 8, np.nan, 2]
4760 fig2, (ax2, ax3, ax4) = plt.subplots(nrows=3, figsize=(4, 8))
4761 ax2.vlines(x2, 0, y2, colors='g', linewidth=5)
4762
4763 x3 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
4764 y3 = [np.nan, 2, -6, 3, 8, 2]
4765 ax3.vlines(x3, 0, y3, colors='r', linewidth=3, linestyle='--')
4766
4767 x4 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]
4768 y4 = [np.nan, 2, -6, 3, 8, np.nan]
4769 ax4.vlines(x4, 0, y4, colors='k', linewidth=2)
4770
4771 # tweak the x-axis so we can see the lines better
4772 for ax in [ax1, ax2, ax3, ax4]:
4773 ax.set_xlim(0, 10)
4774
4775 # check that the y-lims are all automatically the same
4776 assert ax1.get_ylim() == ax2.get_ylim()
4777 assert ax1.get_ylim() == ax3.get_ylim()
4778 assert ax1.get_ylim() == ax4.get_ylim()
4779
4780 fig3, ax5 = plt.subplots()
4781 x5 = np.ma.masked_equal([2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12], 8)
4782 ymin5 = np.ma.masked_equal([0, 1, -1, 0, 2, 1], 2)
4783 ymax5 = np.ma.masked_equal([13, 14, 15, 16, 17, 18], 18)
4784 ax5.vlines(x5, ymin5, ymax5, colors='k', linewidth=2)
4785 ax5.set_xlim(0, 15)

◆ test_zoom_inset()

matplotlib.tests.test_axes.test_zoom_inset ( )
6920def test_zoom_inset():
6921 dx, dy = 0.05, 0.05
6922 # generate 2 2d grids for the x & y bounds
6923 y, x = np.mgrid[slice(1, 5 + dy, dy),
6924 slice(1, 5 + dx, dx)]
6925 z = np.sin(x)**10 + np.cos(10 + y*x) * np.cos(x)
6926
6927 fig, ax = plt.subplots()
6928 ax.pcolormesh(x, y, z[:-1, :-1])
6929 ax.set_aspect(1.)
6930 ax.apply_aspect()
6931 # we need to apply_aspect to make the drawing below work.
6932
6933 # Make the inset_axes... Position axes coordinates...
6934 axin1 = ax.inset_axes([0.7, 0.7, 0.35, 0.35])
6935 # redraw the data in the inset axes...
6936 axin1.pcolormesh(x, y, z[:-1, :-1])
6937 axin1.set_xlim([1.5, 2.15])
6938 axin1.set_ylim([2, 2.5])
6939 axin1.set_aspect(ax.get_aspect())
6940
6941 rec, connectors = ax.indicate_inset_zoom(axin1)
6942 assert len(connectors) == 4
6943 fig.canvas.draw()
6944 xx = np.array([[1.5, 2.],
6945 [2.15, 2.5]])
6946 assert np.all(rec.get_bbox().get_points() == xx)
6947 xx = np.array([[0.6325, 0.692308],
6948 [0.8425, 0.907692]])
6949 np.testing.assert_allclose(
6950 axin1.get_position().get_points(), xx, rtol=1e-4)
6951
6952
